  "prompt": "What universities does Immune Design recruit new grads from? What majors are they looking for?",
  "response": "Immune Design, now part of Merck & Co., Inc. after its acquisition in 2019, recruits new graduates from a variety of universities, focusing primarily on those with strong programs in life sciences, biotechnology, and related fields. Here are some of the universities and majors that Immune Design (and now Merck) have traditionally targeted:\n\n### Universities:\n1. **University of California, Berkeley**\n2. **Stanford University**\n3. **Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)**\n4. **University of California, San Francisco**\n5. **University of Washington**\n6. **Harvard University**\n7. **Johns Hopkins University**\n8. **California Institute of Technology (Caltech)**\n9. **University of Pennsylvania**\n10. **Cornell University**\n\n### Majors:\n1. **Biochemistry**\n2. **Molecular Biology**\n3. **Biotechnology**\n4. **Immunology**\n5. **Bioengineering**\n6. **Chemical Engineering**\n7. **Pharmacology**\n8. **Genetics**\n9. **Microbiology**\n10. **Biomedical Engineering**\n\n### Additional Considerations:\n- **Research Experience:** Candidates with hands-on research experience, particularly in immunology or oncology, are highly valued.\n- **Internships:** Previous internships at biotech or pharmaceutical companies can be a significant advantage.\n- **Publications:** Any published research in relevant scientific journals can enhance a candidate's profile.\n\nPlease note that the specific universities and majors may vary based on current company needs and the evolving focus of Merck's research and development efforts. It's always a good idea to check the careers section of Merck's website for the most up-to-date information on recruitment and preferred qualifications.",
